    Date:        Thu, 9 Apr 87 08:41:32 PST
    From:        postel@bel.isi.edu (Jon Postel)
    Message-ID:  &lt;8704091641.AA02272@bel.isi.edu&gt;

    I'd be very pleased in someone in the UK had a machine named "EDU.ISI.UK".

This is fascinating, given the following excerpt from appendix B of RFC819,
which you might remember ...

   To satisfy the required distinction of simple names for proper
   resolution at all levels, a naming authority needs to ensure the
   simple name to be assigned distinct from those in the name server
   databases at the endpoint naming domains within its domain.

This sentence, out of context, is almost impossible to understand (to
me anyway), but if you go find it in the rfc, I think its clear that
it intends that EDU wouldn't be permitted here.

I would actually appreciate a "ruling" on exactly this point.  There
has been a move to create a subdomain of AU (which I administer)
called "EDU" - there has been a lot of argument against that, largely
using either rfc819 as direct authority, or using the same arguments
as used in rfc819 to arive at this conclusion.

Is rfc819 regarded as being still of good standing?

If so, its worth pointing out that A.ISI.EDU is not a legal domain name!

That is, "A" is not a legal &lt;simple-name&gt; according to the BNF
syntax given in Appendix A (page 10).

Robert Elz	kre@munnari.oz.au	kre%munnari.oz@seismo.css.gov

